```
var query= @&quot;Select islemtipi, sum(AlcT), sum(BrcT), sum(KdvTop), sum(iskonto) 
             from carih Where FirmaKodu =@code
             and islemtipi = @item1 or islemtipi =@item2 or islemtipi = @item3
    or islemtipi = @item4 and (Tarih&gt;= @from  and Tarih &lt;=@to)
    group by islemtipi&quot;;
var rapor = db.Database.SqlQuery&lt;ENT_carih&gt;(query,
                new SqlParameter(&quot;@code&quot;,&quot;001&quot;),
                new SqlParameter(&quot;@item1&quot;,&quot;Satış Faturası&quot;),
                ...
                new SqlParameter(&quot;@from&quot;,fromDate.Date),
                new SqlParameter(&quot;@to&quot;,toDate.Date),
            ).ToList();
```

EF will generate a proper parameterized query from this and pass the strings as Unicode (nvarchar) parameters. Numbers, dates etc will be passed as strongly-typed parameters too. If the `from` and `to` parameters need to be `date` instead of `datetime`, one can create a `date` typed parameter with [one of the constructors that accept a data type](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.data.sqlclient.sqlparameter.-ctor?view=netframework-4.8#System_Data_SqlClient_SqlParameter__ctor_System_String_System_Data_SqlDbType_) :

    new SqlParameter(&quot;@from&quot;,SqlDbType.Date) { Value=fromDate.Date}

